â“ ğ—¤: Why is String immutable in Java?
ğŸ”¹ In Java, when we say a String is immutable, it means once it is created, it cannot be changed.
 If you try to change it, Java will actually create a new object, not modify the original one.

ğŸ§  But why did Java make String immutable?
âœ… 1. Security:
 String is used in sensitive areas like file paths, database URLs, and network connections.
 If it could be changed, hackers might easily break things.

âœ… 2. Memory Efficiency (String Pool):
 Java stores strings in a special memory area called the String pool.
 Since strings donâ€™t change, Java can reuse them to save memory.

âœ… 3. Thread Safety:
 Multiple threads can use the same string without problems, because it canâ€™t change.
*************************

Letâ€™s decode it with simplicity ğŸ‘‡

ğŸ”¹ A HashMap stores key-value pairs using a hashing mechanism.
ğŸ”¹ When two keys hash to the same index, itâ€™s called a collision ğŸš§.
ğŸ”¹ But how does it handle these collisions? ğŸ¤¨

âœ¨ Hereâ€™s the internal magic:

1ï¸âƒ£ Bucket System ğŸª£
Each index in the HashMap array is a bucket that can hold multiple entries.

2ï¸âƒ£ Chaining using Linked List ğŸ”—
Initially, Java uses a linked list to store multiple entries in the same bucket.

3ï¸âƒ£ Switch to Tree after Threshold ğŸŒ³
If too many collisions happen at the same index (more than 8), Java 8+ converts the bucket to a Red-Black Tree for faster lookup time â€” from O(n) to O(log n)
