Java Internals: Hashmap

ğŸ§  You Need to Store 500 Entries in a HashMap - What Would You Do?

Letâ€™s say youâ€™re building a system to store information about the Fortune 500 companies.

You know youâ€™ll have exactly 500 entries.

So how do you initialize your HashMap?

// Option 1: Default constructor
Map<Integer, CompanyDetails> map = new HashMap<>();

// Option 2: Set initial capacity
Map<Integer, CompanyDetails> map = new HashMap<>(500);

Seems logical, right?

But

ğŸ” What actually happens under the hood?

Option 1 - Default constructor:
 â€¢ Starts with 16 buckets
 â€¢ Inserts 500 entries â†’ triggers multiple internal resizes
 â€¢ Each resize = rehashing + memory copy = performance hit

Option 2 - Specifying 500:
 â€¢ Internally rounded to 512 buckets
 â€¢ But thereâ€™s a hidden threshold: only 75% can be filled before resize
 â€¢ So adding 500 entries? Still triggers another resize to 1024


âœ… Whatâ€™s the smarter choice?

You need to account for that hidden threshold a.k.a the load factor (default = 0.75).

To avoid resizing, use:

int expectedSize = 500;
int capacity = (int)(expectedSize / 0.75f) + 1; // ~668
Map<Integer, CompanyDetails> map = new HashMap<>(capacity);


 â€¢ Prevents resizing
 â€¢ Saves CPU cycles
 â€¢ Predictable memory usage

