hy You Should Always Use @Transactional Carefully in Spring

When working with databases in Spring, it's tempting to put @Transactional on every method. But here's what Iâ€™ve learned after working on real-world Java backend systems:

1- Donâ€™t use @Transactional on private methods
 Spring uses proxies for transaction management. Private methods wonâ€™t be intercepted â€” your transaction wonâ€™t work!

2- Be mindful of self-invocation
 Calling a @Transactional method from another method in the same class? It wonâ€™t work â€” because the proxy isnâ€™t used internally.

3- Use proper propagation and isolation levels
 Not all transactions are created equal. Understand REQUIRED, REQUIRES_NEW, and SUPPORTS â€” it can make or break consistency.

4- Exception handling matters
 By default, Spring rolls back only on unchecked exceptions. Want rollback on checked exceptions too? Use:
 @Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

5- Avoid overuse
 Transactional boundaries should be clearly defined. Too large â€” and you lock resources. Too small â€” and you risk partial failure.
