Java Internals: Why hashCode() and equals() Are So Famous in Interviews

ğŸ§  Ever wonder why interviewers love this question?
Because it breaks your code silently - even when everything looks right.
Hereâ€™s a real-world analogy ğŸ‘‡

ğŸ¢ Imagine This - You're managing a companyâ€™s employee database.
You hire Krishna (ID: 101) and add him to your office entry system (a HashSet):

Set<Employee> entrySystem = new HashSet<>();
entrySystem.add(new Employee("Krishna", 101));

Later, Krishna shows up at the door. The system checks:

entrySystem.contains(new Employee("Krishna", 101)); // âŒ Access Denied?!

Butâ€¦ why?! Same name, same ID.

ğŸ” The Reason
Java doesnâ€™t compare by data - it uses:
hashCode() â†’ to find the right bucket
equals() â†’ to check if itâ€™s a match

If you donâ€™t override them, Java compares memory locations - so Krishna looks like a stranger.


âœ… The Fix
@Override
public boolean equals(Object o) {
 return this.id == o.id && this.name.equals(o.name);
}

@Override
public int hashCode() {
 return Objects.hash(name, id);
}

Now Krishna gets access âœ… No duplicate entries. No silent bugs. âœ…

ğŸ¯ Takeaway
HashSet and HashMap need your logic to compare objects.
Thatâ€™s why this question never goes out of fashion in interviews - it shows your understanding of how Java works under the hood.

